The 'Shadow Deployer' skill enables 'Dark Canary' deployments, a technique for testing new agent revisions in production without affecting live traffic. It works by:

1. **Deploying in Shadow Mode:** Deploys a new revision of the agent alongside the existing one, but the new revision does not serve live traffic. Instead, it processes a subset of requests in parallel.
2. **Revision Tagging:** Uses unique tags (e.g., `v1.2-shadow`) to distinguish between the shadow and production revisions.
3. **Traffic Mirroring:** Mirrors a percentage of production traffic to the shadow revision for evaluation.
4. **Automated Rollback:** If the shadow revision fails evaluation metrics, it can be automatically rolled back without impacting users.

Example Terraform configuration for a shadow deployment:
hcl
resource "google_cloud_run_service" "agent_shadow" {
  name     = "agent-shadow-revision"
  location = "us-central1"
  template {
    metadata {
      annotations = {
        "run.googleapis.com/launch-stage" = "BETA"
        "run.googleapis.com/revision-tag" = "shadow-v1.2"
      }
    }
    spec {
      containers {
        image = "gcr.io/project-id/agent-image:shadow-v1.2"
      }
    }
  }
}


This approach ensures safe and gradual rollouts of new agent versions.
